      {
        "paragraph_index": 3,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insight\n\nThe ~9 log-unit advantage of EDTA over NTA is a textbook illustration of the **chelate effect** and **denticity**. EDTA is a hexadentate ligand (2 N + 4 carboxylate O donors) that fully wraps around Fe³⁺, while NTA is only tetradentate (1 N + 3 carboxylate O donors). The two additional donor groups in EDTA provide extra coordination and a much larger entropic driving force for complex formation. This difference is why EDTA is the preferred chelator in analytical chemistry (e.g., complexometric titrations) and in environmental remediation of iron-contaminated systems, where near-quantitative metal sequestration is required.\n\n*Data source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (SRD-46)*",
